State Management Audit — FinCoach UI
What We Have Today
Global State: One context (UserContext) using useReducer. Stores user profile and dashboard preferences. Works correctly — re-fetches on app init, survives refresh.

Everything else: Raw useState + useEffect inside each page. No caching. No shared request state.

Result: Every time a user navigates to a page or refreshes, every API call fires again from scratch. Pagination position is lost. Search queries vanish. Account toggles reset. The obligations "vanish" bug we just fixed is a direct symptom — we had to manually wire optimistic updates because there was no cache to update.

What we need: Keep UserContext for auth/preferences. Add TanStack Query for all server data.

Why TanStack Query
TanStack Query is a server-state library. It separates server data (what the API returns) from UI state (what the user is doing). You define a query key + fetch function once. Any component that needs that data calls the same hook. Under the hood:

The first component to mount fires the request
Other components share the same in-flight request (deduplication)
Data is cached by query key for a configurable stale time
Navigating away and back does a background refetch but shows cached data instantly
Mutations (create/update/delete) can invalidate related queries or do optimistic updates declaratively
Loading, error, and success states come built-in — no boilerplate isLoading flags
Task Document
TASK 1 — Install and configure TanStack Query
Goal: Add TanStack Query to the project and wire up the provider.

Steps:

1.1 Install the package


cd ui
npm install @tanstack/react-query
Also install the devtools (visible only in dev builds, very useful):


npm install @tanstack/react-query-devtools
1.2 Create the QueryClient

Create a new file src/lib/queryClient.ts:


import { QueryClient } from '@tanstack/react-query';

export const queryClient = new QueryClient({
  defaultOptions: {
    queries: {
      staleTime: 1000 * 60 * 5,      // data stays fresh for 5 minutes
      gcTime: 1000 * 60 * 10,         // cache held for 10 minutes after unused
      retry: 2,                        // retry failed requests twice
      refetchOnWindowFocus: false,     // don't refetch when user switches tabs
    },
  },
});
What staleTime means: If the same query was fetched less than 5 minutes ago, TanStack Query serves the cached value and does NOT fire a network request. After 5 minutes, the data is considered "stale" — it still shows the cached value immediately but fires a background refetch to update it. This is what eliminates the blank screen on navigation.

1.3 Wrap the app in the provider

Open src/App.tsx. Currently it only has <UserProvider>. Add QueryClientProvider wrapping everything:


import { QueryClientProvider } from '@tanstack/react-query';
import { ReactQueryDevtools } from '@tanstack/react-query-devtools';
import { queryClient } from './lib/queryClient';

// Inside the return:
<QueryClientProvider client={queryClient}>
  <UserProvider>
    {/* existing IonApp / router / routes */}
  </UserProvider>
  <ReactQueryDevtools initialIsOpen={false} />
</QueryClientProvider>
ReactQueryDevtools renders nothing in production builds. It shows a floating button in dev where you can inspect every cached query, their state, and manually invalidate them.

TASK 2 — Define query keys
Goal: Create a centralised file for all query keys. This is important because query keys are how TanStack Query identifies cached data. If you write the key differently in two places, you get two separate caches and invalidation won't work.

Create src/lib/queryKeys.ts:


export const queryKeys = {
  // User
  userProfile: () => ['user', 'profile'] as const,
  userPreferences: () => ['user', 'preferences'] as const,

  // Transactions
  transactions: (filters: Record<string, unknown>) => ['transactions', filters] as const,
  transaction: (id: string) => ['transactions', id] as const,
  monthTotals: (year: number, month: number) => ['transactions', 'totals', year, month] as const,

  // Accounts
  accounts: (filters?: Record<string, unknown>) => ['accounts', filters ?? {}] as const,
  accountStats: (dateFrom: string, dateTo: string) => ['accounts', 'stats', dateFrom, dateTo] as const,

  // Categories
  categories: () => ['categories'] as const,

  // Stats / Analytics
  dailySummary: (year: number, month: number) => ['stats', 'daily', year, month] as const,
  categoryBudgets: (year: number, month: number) => ['stats', 'categoryBudgets', year, month] as const,
  projectedSummary: (year: number, month: number) => ['stats', 'projected', year, month] as const,
  spendingByCategory: (dateFrom: string, dateTo: string) => ['stats', 'spendingByCategory', dateFrom, dateTo] as const,
  comprehensiveStats: (dateFrom: string, dateTo: string) => ['stats', 'comprehensive', dateFrom, dateTo] as const,

  // Patterns & Obligations
  patterns: (status?: string) => ['patterns', status ?? 'all'] as const,
  upcomingObligations: (daysAhead: number) => ['obligations', 'upcoming', daysAhead] as const,

  // Budget
  customBudgetItems: () => ['budget', 'customItems'] as const,
};
Why arrays as keys: TanStack Query uses deep equality on arrays. ['transactions', { month: 4 }] and ['transactions', { month: 5 }] are different keys and have separate caches. When you call queryClient.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: ['transactions'] }), it invalidates ALL keys that start with 'transactions'.

TASK 3 — Create query hooks for each service
Goal: Wrap every service call in a useQuery hook. Create one file per domain under src/hooks/queries/.

Create the folder: src/hooks/queries/

3.1 src/hooks/queries/useUserQueries.ts


import { useQuery, useMutation, useQueryClient } from '@tanstack/react-query';
import { userService, DashboardPreferences } from '../../services/userService';
import { queryKeys } from '../../lib/queryKeys';

export function useUserProfile() {
  return useQuery({
    queryKey: queryKeys.userProfile(),
    queryFn: () => userService.getUserProfile(),
  });
}

export function useUserPreferences() {
  return useQuery({
    queryKey: queryKeys.userPreferences(),
    queryFn: () => userService.getUserPreferences(),
  });
}

export function useUpdateDashboardPreference() {
  const queryClient = useQueryClient();

  return useMutation({
    mutationFn: ({ key, value }: { key: keyof DashboardPreferences; value: boolean }) =>
      userService.updateDashboardPreference(key, value),

    // Optimistic update — update cache immediately before the API responds
    onMutate: async ({ key, value }) => {
      await queryClient.cancelQueries({ queryKey: queryKeys.userPreferences() });
      const previous = queryClient.getQueryData(queryKeys.userPreferences());

      queryClient.setQueryData(queryKeys.userPreferences(), (old: any) => ({
        ...old,
        ui_preferences: {
          ...old?.ui_preferences,
          dashboard: { ...old?.ui_preferences?.dashboard, [key]: value },
        },
      }));

      return { previous }; // returned as context for onError rollback
    },

    // If the API call fails, roll back the optimistic update
    onError: (_err, _vars, context: any) => {
      queryClient.setQueryData(queryKeys.userPreferences(), context.previous);
    },

    // Always refetch after success or failure to make sure cache is accurate
    onSettled: () => {
      queryClient.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: queryKeys.userPreferences() });
    },
  });
}
